Memmius had been banished, un- justly as he thought, at the mo- ment when he was suing for the consulship. He was now passing a disappointed life in exile, and was so far estranged from Cicero that he had gone to Mytilene to avoid him. He had been annoyed by the importunity of the Epicu- reans, for whom at the best he had apparently great contempt, in spite of the fact that Lucretius had dedi- cated to him the de Rerum lVatura, and his selfish nature brooked no interference with his plans. Finally, Patro, the leader of the Epicurean school, was personally distasteful to him.

Cicero’s itinerary from Minturnae to Athens was as follows : Cumae, Beneventum, May 1 1; Venusia, May 14; Tarentum, May 18; Brun- disium, May 22; Actium, June 143
